rocess also becomes tedious because you have to verify all the test data to confirm the SQL condition was actually what drove the outcome. These context details explain the reasoning behind the recommendation, though the core decision—to use component class unit tests—is already captured in the knowledge file. The problem context around SQL verification difficulty and review overhead is useful background, but the core implementation guidance—separating logic into testable component classes and using direct variable setup—is what matters for actually applying this pattern.\n\nNow I'm cross-checking the knowledge file against the source material to catch any fabrications or misalignments, particularly around the Japanese phrasing and whether the captured guidance accurately reflects what was originally stated.\n\nThe source structure is a FAQ format with question and answer sections, but there's no hierarchical heading breakdown beyond the main title, so keeping everything in a single section makes sense. The knowledge file captures the solution effectively, though it omits the problem context that explains why request unit tests for SQL coverage are problematic and why verification is difficult. Since the core recommendation stands independently, this feels acceptable for the use case.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":17153,"cache_read_input_tokens":29807,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":17153,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":8},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"86ecfe02-d52f-4f2c-99a3-1a3574cdcbe3","uuid":"5d175719-4472-4128-bc2f-c5ed76318f02"}
